segments.text: I went to class that afternoon with a Western shirt on that I had cut the sleeves out of because, you know, working in the oil field while I was bustled up and everything and had on a pair of Levi's and boots, Western boots.
And we had the first hour.
Everything went along just fine and took our break.
in this was in a little anatomy building out behind the
TTI, I don't know if you know which building I'm referring to.
Over on the main campus.
Yeah, it's on the main campus there between Zachary and TTI, that little building.
And so we were on the second floor of that for that lab.
And so we went out in the hall to take our break.
And he joined in, which was very commonplace among several of the faculty.

that was a part of the routine that they join the students in the hall in a very unobtrusive manner but still interact and get to know students and so first thing I knew in that hall here was this man standing right at me you know I mean he was up about like this and he was looked and he touched my shirt some way
And I got, and he, I don't remember exactly what he said, but, in words, but what he communicated was, you're not dressed right, and I don't want to see you this way again.
So he didn't.
But he didn't have to make a big thing of it, but he made his way through all, I mean, he didn't just slug me out.
He...
dressed up the whole class within that first week.
The first week, we covered subject matter, but he also kind of set the tone for us going through school as to the way that he expected.
His unforgettable speech was the first day of a class, of a course?
Yes.
And what was the course?
Well, it was the, we had one lecture
and 12 hours of lab in the gross anatomy for the fall semester.
We're all 64 in that.
They all heard it from him.
In lecture.
That was the baptism.
Yeah.
OK. And then what were some other important first year courses, experiences?
Well, he had Raymond Reiser for biochemistry, an extremely knowledgeable man, but not a very effective teacher at the undergraduate level.
I had him later in a graduate course and found him to be at that was his level.
He was a graduate teacher.
He was from arts and sciences.
Was he full time in the vet school then?
No.
See, we also had Harry Kunkel.
They were both from agriculture.
Biochemistry was in agriculture at that time.
And as it turns out, see, Harry Kunkel is one of the teachers that's pretty high on, you know, he's pretty high on the pinnacle in my view.
Now, what was special about his teachings?
Well, he was very well informed and very interested in new things, new information.
And a good lecturer, very well organized in the way he presented his subject matter.
He presented a very complex subject matter in a very clear way.
And of course, one of the ways that he endeared himself to my class, well, to me, and I think most, if not all, of my class was that he clarified Dr. Reiser's lectures to us.
Did you all have nicknames for Kunkel and Reiser?
Because over on the other campus, Uncle Kunkel's Mystery Hour.
was the course he taught.
And I've never heard one for Riser.
I don't remember a nickname, but he was a source of great frustration to us.
He would try to do things, you know, there were things that were thought to be important to teach beginning biochemistry students that were
way long since uh uh he he had long since gotten away from that like telling enantiomorphs two chemicals and that are almost mirror images of each other well that i guess are mirror images and uh he
He just bum-puzzled us with that, with his illustrations.

He was like physics potter in that he would go to great lengths to devote a lot of thought to how he was going to approach explaining this so that we would know or it would be understanding to us, and yet we just couldn't get it.
Were you all aware that he was Jewish?
Yeah.
Did that matter?
I don't think, it may have to some, but I don't think so.
You were in class or lab all day, five and a half days, did you all have Saturday classes too?
Yeah.
Five and a half days?
It's pretty full, see Benny Kemp was a lab instructor in biochemistry, so he was working on his PhD at that time, and Benny helped tremendously with
to fill in the gaps for us with the Bible camp.
Now, you all refer to yourselves as first year vet students?
Yeah.
You didn't say freshman?
Uh-uh.
First year.
And did you all begin to refer to yourselves as we're in the vet class of
Is that right?
Okay, that's right.
And so two years of pre-vet, normally, and then?
Four years.
Four, okay.
That first year, where were you living?
I lived on campus in the core area.
We had a dorm, we were in dorm two.
Were you still in the core?
No.
So you ate in... We ate in Duncan Hall.
Duncan, in civilian outfits.
Yeah.
And you were free of all of that.
Mm-hmm.
And how did you feel about that, about being free of the court?
Yeah, it was a good feeling just to watch them fall out.
Usually, like for lunch, we were...
typically we would get there after they had marched in.
And as you look back that lecture from Dr. Price and that course, what were some other important experiences that first year for you as a future veterinarian?
Well,
I think the animal nutrition course that Harry Kunkel taught was very, well it excited me because this was, to me this was very detailed, involved information.
But it was a clear advancement of information about animals that I had not known.
And I thought, well, this is what vet school is going to be about when I get beyond these basics.
And so that was a very important positive development.
Now, in the spring, we had large animal gross anatomy, and that was taught by a man by the name of Gibbs, Leon Gibbs, who later fell into, had some disciplinary difficulties.
And he was in the same department.
Of course, the Department of Veterinary Anatomy consisted of Dr. Miliff Head,
Al Price and Leon Gibbs and Al Price was obviously the fair-haired boy and Leon just was not oriented he was not an outgoing sort of a person and so he wound up being kind of the

the black sheep of the faculty at least from our experience and students tried to play pranks you know to catch him you know for example when we were see we dissected equine cadavers and the students would different groups of course you know each each of us were assigned to a group that had a

particular cadaver and during the first half of the semester well these would be suspended by chain or heavy rope from the ceiling and they were standing there and so we did a great deal of the dissection of the standing animal and students would go to very elaborate means to

put a nerve inside of artery or something like that and if we found a parasite in the digestive tract we'll take that out and put it in the heart and then call him over and want to know you know very innocently well what's this so it just just uh
bedeviled the poor man.
Did he ever fall prey to those?
Did he ever believe?
Well, sometimes it would just about get him in.
There were the most flagrant and the one that really just we didn't know there for a week or two whether any of us were going to pass the course.

that were in that section, but one of our classmates, and he's a friend of mine, lives in Kerrville now, retired there, and he, after we had, this was pretty far into the semester, and his horse was a gelding, and so he cut the penis off,

this particular day and then went over to a neighboring one that was a mare and it was quite a chore but he stuffed that into the tract of the mare and left it there till I think another it was another lab and he he got the students to

that had that and maybe he was over there and he yeah I think that's the way it was he they were all milling around and he called held up his hand Dr. Gibbs would you come over and help us with this we can't figure out what this is right here and so Dr. Gibbs pulled that out you know and it just caught him you know and went all over him it wasn't that bad a thing but it
He was really, really angry.
And he was an individual who got very red.
When he got angry, he got red in the face.
And he really got, and he just left and didn't come back in for the lab.
That, how academically demanding was that first year of vet school compared to what you'd had before?
Well, it was, for me, it was easier than the, well, that summer with inorganic chemistry because of the time crunch.
And then in the sophomore year, I did well in organic chemistry and made B's in physics, but I made a B and an A in organic, the two courses.
But I really had to work at them.
And that was just a matter of disciplining yourself to work on something that really wasn't your primary interest.
But this stuff, you know, these things were all really quite interesting.
And I found them to be.
Based on what you now know,
How would you rate the quality of the instruction that first year?
Was it up to date for that era?
Yeah.
What about the applied compared to the theoretical?
Did it have an appropriate blend of those two?
Yeah.
Not to the extent that the students receive now, but I thought there was enough applied in it to serve as a teaser just to kind of keep your interest up.
But there still was just a tremendous amount.
We were expected to learn so much more

anatomy so many more terms than they are now they they just don't worry that much with with total comprehensive anatomy they'll like you know around a joint they don't we had to know we were expected to know any and every structure now that was an impossibility but still that was the challenge to us and we were
given access to all of that information.
Now the point will be that this is the knee joint or the stifle joint, and these are the important structures you should know about, and so that's the approach that's used.
As far as you could tell at that time and in looking back,
Was there any attempt to intimidate y'all, like the old thing, look on left and right, that they used to do with fish?
Left and right, one of you's not going to be here three years from now.
Was there any of that in vet school?
Or did you feel they were encouraging all of you?
Dr. Turk would do this occasionally, but he wasn't serious about it.
Did you have him as a freshman?
No.
No.
So you were encouraged.
Was there any effort to emphasize small animal, large animal, applied or theoretical?
Not until you got...
The emphasis the first three years was in total veterinary education.
And the goal...
The goal of that faculty was to educate an individual to be as well-rounded a veterinarian as possible with no deficiencies, no areas of glaring deficiency.
and the expectation was that the individual would be functional in both in treating both pets and livestock but would acquire the real
finesse and so on after graduation.
And you continued to think of a large animal as your goal?
Well, no, I did until I worked after, in a practice, but after my

third year in vet school and before my senior year but you know that was a large fire engine practice as i call it and as many of them were and uh i saw the the not so fun side of livestock working with livestock right uh but back at the at the vet school

as far as y'all knew they hoped everybody would would survive academically and there was encouragement there was positive encouragement generalize about your class where were they from what were their family background geographically their attitudes their values well we had uh
The majority of my class was from smaller towns.
In Texas?
In Texas.
We had a cluster of probably on the order of eight to ten Houstonians in the class.
First generation college students?
Well, a lot of
of particularly the ones from smaller towns was the case.
There were a number of first generation type.
Now we did, in our class we had five or six older, somewhat older students who were 25 to 35 years of age.
And some of them had
been in the service before, and there were various reasons, I guess, for their coming on when they did.
We had several from the class before us.
That is, they spent three years in pre-vet.
But I would say at least half of the class was a two-year
had gone through two-year pre-vet?
About how many of them were farmer ranch boys in background?
Oh, I would have guessed probably on the order of 40.
So maybe two-thirds.
Yeah.
And how many had gone to A&M for their pre-vet?
Probably about two-thirds.
Any out-of-staters then?
Yeah, we had the Louisiana crews.
Oh, that was already?
Uh-huh.
How did they fare?
Well, my class was a little different, a little unusual in that we had a large number
of students, people who started out with us who went to medical school, dropped out and went to medical school, and a couple went to dental school.
I think of 64, I think there were 13 that did that.
And so our class was referred to for a few years as

being that that particular class where so many of them and what were they and this included about uh see we we i think we had nine from louisiana and i think three of them did that went into medical school were there were there any activities early in that first year to bring you all together any social or any other kind of well we had the
What at that time was a glorified, it was a barbecue and a beer bust that the class before us put on for us.
And that's the way it was done for many, many years.
And then probably you may remember the barbecue that this had really expanded
by the seventies in
but we still had one in the first week or two of classes.
And the second year class always was responsible for it.
In your first year, where was it held?
At the VFW grounds on 21, Highway 21.
And faculty and all students came, not just your class?
That's right.
No, no, this was just our class and the sophomore class, the two classes.
And there was a feeling of warmth?
Yeah, we had, there was good rapport established during that.
The faculty all, particularly the faculty who were teaching those classes, it was, you just saw them there.
They didn't, it wasn't something that maybe one or two faculty would show up.
But, you know, with Al Price's value system being around a bunch of beard up students would not have been his idea of a pleasant evening.
But he was there, and he would really join in telling stories and enjoying the stories and things like that.
And so for you and your buddies going through that fall semester, what was, or that whole first year you lived on campus, what was your, what was a typical routine?
You got up, went to chow.
went over to the vet school, and we had a lot of labs.
The labs, you know, the gross anatomy class, for example, just use that as an example, we had three four-hour labs a week.
So for each four hours, we got one hour of credit.
See, that was a four-hour course.
We got
We had one hour of lecture and three, four hour labs.
So that was a four hour course.
13 hours of contact time with that.
That was cut back then a little later on in the scheme of things.
I'm not talking about while I was a student, but while I was on the faculty.
When we went through the trimester, see, everything, all the four hour labs were reduced to a three hour lab.
And then in the 70s, well, most of the three-hour labs were reduced to a two-hour lab.
You went over to the vet school.
You were there all morning.
Did you all go back to Duncan for supper?
I mean, for lunch?
For lunch, uh-huh.
And we'd get there.
Usually, we were 12, 10, 12, 15 getting there.
We had to eat.
And then be right back.
For a one o'clock.
Uh-huh.
Then you're there all afternoon.
Then back to Chow where there are some labs at night.
But did you go back to the vet school at night or did you study in your room?
Both.
As we began to prepare for exams, well, we'd often go back.
But, see, we were a large...
number of us were living in dorm two, and so we were really concentrated, and the class ahead of us were living in that particular dorm, so we had a concentration of vet students.
Was there good bull going on elsewhere in the dorm?
There'd be some nights, yeah, there'd be.
But the vet students, y'all weren't involved in that?
Not too much.
OK, so wasn't any drown outs and all that.
Then Saturday in class or lab till noon.
Yeah.
And by and large, then you took Saturday afternoon and Sunday off.
That was pretty much the routine.
Now, we didn't have, you know, we'd have an hour
free time in the morning maybe or maybe two hours sometimes.
What would you do with that?

Well when we were I remember when we were sophomores or our second year in vet school we were living in I lived in law hall with a group and we would bust it back if we sometimes when we had an hour but especially if we had a two hour and I think there was a
maybe Tuesdays and Thursdays, we may have had a two-hour break in the middle of the morning.
And we'd go back to the room and play shoot the moon.
That just got to be a big thing with the group, and we were very competitive with it.
So rather than studying like theoretically you would, and like we were more inclined to do as freshmen,
I mean, our first year, we...
Right, and you vet students attended Silver Taps, and you went to Bonfire.
The ones that lived on campus, uh-huh.
But when you were a vet student, you all didn't work on...
Didn't work on Bonfire, uh-uh.
Academically, the first year, how did it go?
It went well.
And were grades then posted publicly in vet school?
Oh, yeah.
I did well in vet school.
I thought you had.
There were five of us that kind of built a little, well, there was a gap anyway between.
Did the five of y'all get a nickname?
Well.
That's tellable?
Trying to think of the group.
We had, the top student in our class was a guy by the name of Wallace Klebb.
Wally was the captain of the track team his senior year.
And he's been, and he was president of the Letterman's, he's been president of the Letterman's.
CLEB or KLEB?
KLEB.
Wallace Klebb.
He practiced for many, many years in Houston, small animal practice, in his century.
